## 🟢 Low Issues

### L-1 · `SafariView` is used but never defined in the reviewed files
**Files**: [OnboardingView.swift](file:///Users/michele/Documents/GitHub/Ninety-app/Ninety/View/Root/OnboardingView.swift#L104), [SettingsView.swift](file:///Users/michele/Documents/GitHub/Ninety-app/Ninety/View/Settings/SettingsView.swift#L307)

`SafariView(url:)` is referenced but not defined in any reviewed file. It's presumably a `UIViewControllerRepresentable` wrapper for `SFSafariViewController`. Ensure it exists and handles edge cases (no internet, invalid URL).

---

### L-2 · `DiagnosticsView` log display is unbounded in memory
**File**: [DiagnosticsView.swift](file:///Users/michele/Documents/GitHub/Ninety-app/Ninety/View/Root/DiagnosticsView.swift#L132)

`sleepManager.logs.prefix(5000).reversed()` — the underlying `logs` array can grow without bound during a long session. While the view caps display at 5000, the backing array continues to consume memory.

> [!TIP]
> **Fix**: Cap `logs` to a maximum size (e.g. ring buffer of 10,000 entries).

---

### L-3 · `"Alarm saved"` in WatchSetup is hardcoded English
**File**: [ScheduleView+WatchSetup.swift](file:///Users/michele/Documents/GitHub/Ninety-app/Ninety/View/Schedule/ScheduleView+WatchSetup.swift#L88-L102)

`"Alarm saved".localized(for: appLanguage)` etc. — these strings are only translated in some languages. The `.localized()` call returns the English fallback silently when a translation is missing, but there's no compile-time check for completeness.

---

### L-4 · Magic numbers throughout the codebase
**Files**: Multiple

Examples:
- `300` (gap threshold) — should be named `epochGapResetThreshold`
- `12_000` (max pending payloads) — should be named
- `30 * 60` (monitoring lead time) — already named on Watch side but not on iOS side
- `0.08` (motion threshold) — named on Watch but not referenced consistently

---

### L-5 · `NinetyApp.swift` force-initializes singletons with `_ =`
**File**: [NinetyApp.swift](file:///Users/michele/Documents/GitHub/Ninety-app/Ninety/NinetyApp.swift)

`_ = SleepSessionManager.shared` and `_ = SmartAlarmManager.shared` are used to trigger initialization. This works but is an anti-pattern. Consider making these `@StateObject` properties or using an explicit `setup()` method.

---

### L-6 · `WatchCopy.swift` file header says "ContentView.swift"
**File**: [WatchCopy.swift](file:///Users/michele/Documents/GitHub/Ninety-app/NinetyWatch%20Watch%20App/WatchCopy.swift#L1-L3)

The file header comment says `ContentView.swift` — this is a copy-paste artifact.

---

### L-7 · `GuidedTourView` uses raw `Int` for step navigation
**File**: [GuidedTourView.swift](file:///Users/michele/Documents/GitHub/Ninety-app/Ninety/View/Root/GuidedTourView.swift#L250-L259)

`step.rawValue - 1` / `step.rawValue + 1` with a guard. This works but adding/removing/reordering steps will break silently. Consider using `CaseIterable` indices instead.

---

### L-8 · `.setAlarm` WatchCopy key is not translated
**File**: [WatchCopy.swift](file:///Users/michele/Documents/GitHub/Ninety-app/NinetyWatch%20Watch%20App/WatchCopy.swift)

The `.setAlarm` key returns `"Set Ninety Alarm"` in **all** languages (Italian, Spanish, Chinese, Arabic). This appears to be a missed translation.

---

### L-9 · `buttonTint` computed property in `WatchAlarmSetupView` is defined but never used
**File**: [ContentView.swift](file:///Users/michele/Documents/GitHub/Ninety-app/NinetyWatch%20Watch%20App/ContentView.swift#L287-L298)

The `buttonTint` computed property returns per-state colors but is never referenced in the view body. Dead code.

---

### L-10 · `handleScheduledAlarmReached` has identical behavior in both branches
**File**: [WatchSensorManager+PayloadDelivery.swift](file:///Users/michele/Documents/GitHub/Ninety-app/NinetyWatch%20Watch%20App/WatchSensorManager+PayloadDelivery.swift#L75-L96)

```swift
if phoneReachable {
    clearScheduledAlarmAndMonitoring(detail: "Watch smart wake active", state: .completed, keepHapticsRunning: true)
} else {
    clearScheduledAlarmAndMonitoring(detail: reason, state: .completed, keepHapticsRunning: true)
}
```

The only difference is the `detail` string. This suggests the phone-reachable branch was meant to have different behaviour (e.g. not starting haptics locally when the phone handles the alarm).

